00:03:21.630 --> 00:03:23.820
So the question
I'm dealing with is

00:03:23.820 --> 00:03:26.490
how old is the human species.

00:03:26.490 --> 00:03:29.530
Today, the most common
answer to that question

00:03:29.530 --> 00:03:34.960
comes from the modern followers
of Charles Darwin, who

00:03:34.960 --> 00:03:37.710
propose that the
first humans like

00:03:37.710 --> 00:03:43.100
us came into existence less
than 200,000 years ago.

00:03:43.100 --> 00:03:44.890
Before that, they
would say there

00:03:44.890 --> 00:03:48.330
were no humans like us
present on this planet,

00:03:48.330 --> 00:03:51.820
simply more primitive,
ape-like human ancestors.

00:03:53.480 --> 00:03:56.500
However, the Puranas,
the historical writings

00:03:56.500 --> 00:03:59.940
of ancient India,
give a different idea,

00:03:59.940 --> 00:04:02.560
namely that humans
have been present

00:04:02.560 --> 00:04:06.740
for vast periods of time
on this planet going back

00:04:06.740 --> 00:04:08.655
many millions of years.

00:04:10.080 --> 00:04:12.740
Now of course, in
scientific circles,

00:04:12.740 --> 00:04:17.970
I wouldn't expect anyone
to take a statement

00:04:17.970 --> 00:04:21.510
from some ancient
writings as evidence.

00:04:21.510 --> 00:04:29.240
So in the scientific circles
where I'm invited to speak,

00:04:29.240 --> 00:04:31.850
I do something else.

00:04:31.850 --> 00:04:39.290
I make a prediction, namely
if what the Puranas say

00:04:39.290 --> 00:04:41.940
about human antiquity
is true, there

00:04:41.940 --> 00:04:45.220
should be reports of
archaeological evidence

00:04:45.220 --> 00:04:50.410
for humans existing much further
back in time than 200,000

00:04:50.410 --> 00:04:54.970
years ago, perhaps going
back many millions of years.

00:04:54.970 --> 00:04:59.040
So my method for
testing that prediction

00:04:59.040 --> 00:05:03.670
is to examine all archaeological
reports from the time of Darwin

00:05:03.670 --> 00:05:04.330
to the present.

00:05:05.410 --> 00:05:07.090
And not just in English.

00:05:07.090 --> 00:05:09.010
I have a reading
knowledge of most

00:05:09.010 --> 00:05:10.985
of the major European languages.

00:05:12.420 --> 00:05:18.560
So when I speak about
examining reports

00:05:18.560 --> 00:05:20.370
from the scientific
literature, I

00:05:20.370 --> 00:05:24.850
mean two kinds of scientific
literature, the primary

00:05:24.850 --> 00:05:27.890
and the secondary
scientific literature.

00:05:27.890 --> 00:05:30.590
By primary scientific
literature,

00:05:30.590 --> 00:05:35.430
I mean original reports by
archaeologists, geologists,

00:05:35.430 --> 00:05:38.650
paleontologists, and
other Earth scientists

00:05:38.650 --> 00:05:43.006
reported in the professional,
peer reviewed, scientific

00:05:43.006 --> 00:05:43.505
literature.

00:05:44.900 --> 00:05:48.110
By secondary literature,
I mean things

00:05:48.110 --> 00:05:51.830
that are based on the primary
literature, such as textbooks,

00:05:51.830 --> 00:05:52.535
for example.

00:05:55.340 --> 00:05:58.620
So I had two principal findings.

00:06:00.224 --> 00:06:05.100
The first finding is
not so surprising.

00:06:05.100 --> 00:06:09.770
There are no reports of evidence
for extreme human antiquity

00:06:09.770 --> 00:06:12.460
in the current secondary
literature, textbooks,

00:06:12.460 --> 00:06:14.910
survey studies, and
things of that sort.

00:06:16.230 --> 00:06:20.026
My second finding was a
little more interesting.

00:06:21.370 --> 00:06:23.480
There are many
reports of evidence

00:06:23.480 --> 00:06:27.210
for extreme human antiquity
in the primary scientific

00:06:27.210 --> 00:06:29.620
literature of past and present.

00:06:31.350 --> 00:06:36.150
So I collected those
reports and this book,

00:06:36.150 --> 00:06:40.920
"Forbidden Archeology,"
which was reviewed

00:06:40.920 --> 00:06:43.780
in most of the
professional, academic,

00:06:43.780 --> 00:06:46.140
and scientific
journals that deal

00:06:46.140 --> 00:06:47.856
with the question
of human origins.

00:06:49.080 --> 00:06:51.995
So this constitutes a
kind of peer review.

00:06:53.420 --> 00:07:00.010
Now, as you might expect, many
of those reviews were negative,

00:07:00.010 --> 00:07:01.820
some extremely so.

00:07:03.250 --> 00:07:08.816
However, quite
surprisingly to me even,

00:07:08.816 --> 00:07:14.900
even some of my critics
were able to point out

00:07:14.900 --> 00:07:18.305
some positive
aspects of the work.

00:07:20.010 --> 00:07:23.880
For example, David Oldroyd,
a noted historian of science,

00:07:23.880 --> 00:07:28.320
in a 28 page review
article about the book

00:07:28.320 --> 00:07:31.160
asked the question, so
has forbidden archeology

00:07:31.160 --> 00:07:33.080
made any contribution
to the literature

00:07:33.080 --> 00:07:34.045
on paleoanthropology.

00:07:35.600 --> 00:07:38.290
Our answer is a guarded
yes for two reasons.

00:07:39.740 --> 00:07:42.270
First, he said, much of
the historical material

00:07:42.270 --> 00:07:46.390
has not been scrutinized
in such detail before.

00:07:46.390 --> 00:07:48.920
In other words, as a
professional historian

00:07:48.920 --> 00:07:52.910
of science dealing with
these particular questions,

00:07:52.910 --> 00:07:55.790
he had not encountered
any work which

00:07:55.790 --> 00:07:58.320
had gone into history
in such depth before.

00:07:58.320 --> 00:08:01.790
And second, he said,
the book raises, quote,

00:08:01.790 --> 00:08:04.230
a central problematic
regarding the lack

00:08:04.230 --> 00:08:06.810
of certainty in
scientific truth claims.

00:08:09.570 --> 00:08:14.390
Now, after the
book was published

00:08:14.390 --> 00:08:16.140
and many of the
reviews came out,

00:08:16.140 --> 00:08:20.540
I began speaking about
