00:08:26.260 --> 00:08:28.785
at a meeting of the World
Archaeological Congress.

00:08:29.980 --> 00:08:32.440
It's the world's largest
international organization

00:08:32.440 --> 00:08:33.650
of archaeologists.

00:08:33.650 --> 00:08:36.299
I presented a paper there
called "Puranic Time

00:08:36.299 --> 00:08:38.690
and The Archaeological Record."

00:08:38.690 --> 00:08:43.950
And that paper was
selected for publication

00:08:43.950 --> 00:08:47.090
in a peer reviewed conference
proceedings volume called

00:08:47.090 --> 00:08:50.150
"Time and Archaeology,"
which came out from Rutledge,

00:08:50.150 --> 00:08:52.065
a major scientific publisher.

00:08:54.500 --> 00:08:58.000
And subsequently, I've
presented papers on my work

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:02.420
at many other meetings of the
World Archaeological Congress,

00:09:02.420 --> 00:09:06.766
and also meetings of
the European Association

00:09:06.766 --> 00:09:07.516
of Archaeologists.

00:09:08.930 --> 00:09:12.420
And the reason I'm
mentioning this

00:09:12.420 --> 00:09:16.620
is just to show that the
kinds of things I'm saying

00:09:16.620 --> 00:09:20.120
are part of the
scientific discourse

00:09:20.120 --> 00:09:23.830
in the scientific
disciplines that

00:09:23.830 --> 00:09:26.020
are related to human origins.

00:09:26.020 --> 00:09:30.220
Now, admittedly, it's
not a popular voice.

00:09:30.220 --> 00:09:34.930
It's an extreme minority
voice limited maybe even

00:09:34.930 --> 00:09:36.355
to a minority of one.

00:09:37.770 --> 00:09:43.200
But still, surprisingly
enough to many people,

00:09:43.200 --> 00:09:46.810
it is a part of the discourse.

00:09:48.450 --> 00:09:52.660
So one of the questions I had
about the kind of evidence I'm

00:09:52.660 --> 00:09:57.460
talking about is
why exactly is it

00:09:57.460 --> 00:10:00.390
missing from the current
secondary literature

00:10:00.390 --> 00:10:02.245
if it's there in the
primary literature.

00:10:03.480 --> 00:10:10.050
And I'm proposing it's because
of a process of knowledge

00:10:10.050 --> 00:10:13.620
filtration that operates
in the world of science.

00:10:13.620 --> 00:10:16.530
And here, I'm not talking
about a Satanic conspiracy

00:10:16.530 --> 00:10:17.585
to suppress truth.

00:10:19.030 --> 00:10:21.410
I'm talking about
something that philosophers

00:10:21.410 --> 00:10:23.810
of science and
historians of science

00:10:23.810 --> 00:10:26.520
have understood for
a long time, namely

00:10:26.520 --> 00:10:31.230
that theoretical preconceptions
can influence how scientists

00:10:31.230 --> 00:10:35.040
may react to different
categories of evidence that

00:10:35.040 --> 00:10:37.160
come to their attention.

00:10:38.740 --> 00:10:41.150
We can call the blue box
the knowledge filter.

00:10:41.150 --> 00:10:44.410
And what it represents
is the dominant consensus

00:10:44.410 --> 00:10:48.280
in the scientific discipline
at a particular point in time.

00:10:48.280 --> 00:10:51.600
And reports of
evidence that conform

00:10:51.600 --> 00:10:56.530
to the dominant consensus will
pass through the knowledge

00:10:56.530 --> 00:10:59.850
filter fairly easily,
whereas reports

00:10:59.850 --> 00:11:02.260
of evidence that
radically contradict

00:11:02.260 --> 00:11:05.540
a dominant consensus
tend to be filtered out,

00:11:05.540 --> 00:11:10.440
ignored, forgotten,
set aside, dismissed.

00:11:12.690 --> 00:11:17.990
And this was something that one
of the reviewers of "Forbidden

00:11:17.990 --> 00:11:21.835
Archeology" noted, the
French archaeologist Marylene

00:11:21.835 --> 00:11:26.430
Patou-Mathis noted in her
review of "Forbidden Archeology"

00:11:26.430 --> 00:11:28.080
in "L'Anthropologie."

00:11:28.080 --> 00:11:31.030
"Cremo and Thompson have
written a provocative work

00:11:31.030 --> 00:11:34.780
that raises the problem of the
influence of the dominant ideas

00:11:34.780 --> 00:11:38.920
of a time period on
scientific research.

00:11:38.920 --> 00:11:41.680
These ideas can
compel the researchers

00:11:41.680 --> 00:11:43.700
to orient their
analyses according

00:11:43.700 --> 00:11:45.990
to the conceptions
that are permitted

00:11:45.990 --> 00:11:48.680
by the scientific community."

00:11:48.680 --> 00:11:53.040
So it was interesting to
me that an archaeologist

00:11:53.040 --> 00:11:56.450
grasped correctly
what the point we

00:11:56.450 --> 00:11:59.460
were trying to make in the book
and wasn't just dismissing it

00:11:59.460 --> 00:12:01.945
as, oh, these are
conspiracy theorists.

00:12:05.220 --> 00:12:09.830
I'm now going to go over
some of the kinds of reports

00:12:09.830 --> 00:12:10.910
that I'm talking about.

00:12:10.910 --> 00:12:14.560
This is Virginia Steen-McIntyre,
an American geologist.

00:12:14.560 --> 00:12:17.900
She was involved in dating
an archaeological site

00:12:17.900 --> 00:12:21.130
at Hueyatlaco in Mexico.

00:12:21.130 --> 00:12:24.600
There, archaeologists had
discovered projectile points

00:12:24.600 --> 00:12:27.770
and other stone
tools and weapons.

00:12:27.770 --> 00:12:30.710
And they were, of
course, interested

00:12:30.710 --> 00:12:32.600
in how all these things were.

00:12:32.600 --> 00:12:34.560
This is the excavation
at Hueyatlaco.

00:12:36.330 --> 00:12:40.100
And the artifacts were
photographed intact

00:12:40.100 --> 00:12:42.180
in the layers of rock in
which they were found.

00:12:43.660 --> 00:12:46.600
Virginia Steen-McIntyre
and her colleagues

00:12:46.600 --> 00:12:50.980
used four different
methods to date the site.

00:12:50.980 --> 00:12:53.080
Animal bones with
butchering marks

00:12:53.080 --> 00:12:56.070
were found in the same
layers with the stone tools.

00:12:56.070 --> 00:12:59.600
The geologists used the
uranium series method

00:12:59.600 --> 00:13:01.000
to date those bones.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:05.380
They got an age
of 245,000 years.

00:13:05.380 --> 00:13:07.500
Above the layer
with the stone tools

00:13:07.500 --> 00:13:09.540
was a layer of volcanic ash.

00:13:09.540 --> 00:13:12.890
The geologists used the Zircon
Fission Track method to date

00:13:12.890 --> 00:13:14.480
that layer of ash.

00:13:14.480 --> 00:13:18.750
They got an age
of 270,000 years.

00:13:18.750 --> 00:13:21.700
Using all four methods
that they employed,

00:13:21.700 --> 00:13:23.580
the geologists
concluded the site

00:13:23.580 --> 00:13:28.170
must be at least
250,000 years old.

00:13:28.170 --> 00:13:32.080
However, the archaeologists
refused to accept it.

00:13:32.080 --> 00:13:36.870
They said humans capable of
making those artifacts didn't

00:13:36.870 --> 00:13:40.930
exist anywhere in the
world 250,000 years ago.

00:13:40.930 --> 00:13:43.600
They hadn't evolved
yet, what to speak

00:13:43.600 --> 00:13:45.470
of being present
in North America.

00:13:46.560 --> 00:13:49.690
They considered the oldest
human presence in North America

00:13:49.690 --> 00:13:52.820
to go back only
about 20,000 years.

00:13:52.820 --> 00:13:55.540
So they refused to publish
the age for the site

00:13:55.540 --> 00:13:58.280
given by their own hand-picked
team of geologists.

00:13:59.320 --> 00:14:01.990
So Virginia Steen-McIntyre
and her colleagues

00:14:01.990 --> 00:14:03.650
were a little surprised by that.

00:14:03.650 --> 00:14:07.250
So they decided to
independently publish

00:14:07.250 --> 00:14:09.580
the age for the site
in a journal called

00:14:09.580 --> 00:14:11.690
"Quaternary Research."

00:14:11.690 --> 00:14:13.890
But when they did
that, they experienced

00:14:13.890 --> 00:14:17.890
an extreme negative backlash
from their colleagues

00:14:17.890 --> 00:14:20.290
in the scientific
world because they

00:14:20.290 --> 00:14:22.740
had dared to publish
something like this.

00:14:23.950 --> 00:14:26.740
Virginia Steen-McIntyre
wrote to one

00:14:26.740 --> 00:14:29.770
of the editors of the journal,
"Not being an anthropologist,

00:14:29.770 --> 00:14:33.800
I didn't realize how deeply
woven into our thought

00:14:33.800 --> 00:14:37.140
the current theory of
human evolution has become.

00:14:37.140 --> 00:14:41.840
Our work at Hueyatlaco has been
rejected by most archaeologists

00:14:41.840 --> 00:14:48.370
because it contradicts
that theory."

00:14:48.370 --> 00:14:52.460
So some of the cases I'm
going to be talking about

00:14:52.460 --> 00:14:55.750
are from the more recent
history of archaeology,

00:14:55.750 --> 00:14:59.400
some from the more distant
history of archaeology.

00:14:59.400 --> 00:15:02.280
Some of the cases
are going to be

00:15:02.280 --> 00:15:06.630
closer to what the
mainstream concepts allow.

00:15:06.630 --> 00:15:10.420
And some are going to be further
and further distant from what

00:15:10.420 --> 00:15:12.820
current ideas would
consider possible.

00:15:13.880 --> 00:15:17.530
This is one of the founders
of modern archaeology, Jacques

00:15:17.530 --> 00:15:18.330
Boucher de Perthes.

00:15:19.540 --> 00:15:24.390
And one of his excavations,
Moulin Quignon near Abbeville

00:15:24.390 --> 00:15:28.780
in Northeastern France, he found
an anatomically modern human

00:15:28.780 --> 00:15:29.280
jawbone.

00:15:30.300 --> 00:15:34.190
He found it in the bottom
layers of his excavation

00:15:34.190 --> 00:15:37.110
with stone tools and weapons.

00:15:37.110 --> 00:15:41.950
According to modern geologists,
that layer at Abbeville

00:15:41.950 --> 00:15:47.200
is about 430,000 years old.

00:15:47.200 --> 00:15:50.390
It was quite a
controversial discovery,

00:15:50.390 --> 00:15:51.835
even in the 19th century.

00:15:53.360 --> 00:15:57.210
Many scientists could
not accept that humans

00:15:57.210 --> 00:16:01.230
existed at that
distant point in time.

00:16:01.230 --> 00:16:05.586
So some of them proposed,
well, Boucher de Perthes

00:16:05.586 --> 00:16:07.085
must have been the
victim of a hoax.

00:16:08.230 --> 00:16:10.310
Somehow or other,
someone must have

00:16:10.310 --> 00:16:16.120
gone to some Roman cemetery,
gotten a jawbone 2,000 or 3,000

00:16:16.120 --> 00:16:19.940
years old and buried it in the
excavation for him to find.

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:23.930
And that's actually
the explanation

00:16:23.930 --> 00:16:26.910
that we see in
today's textbooks.

00:16:26.910 --> 00:16:31.010
However, what we do not
see in today's textbooks is

00:16:31.010 --> 00:16:35.590
that after these hoax
accusations came out,

00:16:35.590 --> 00:16:38.890
Boucher de Perthes made
additional excavations

00:16:38.890 --> 00:16:40.030
at Moulin Quignon.

00:16:41.040 --> 00:16:44.320
And these additional
excavations,

00:16:44.320 --> 00:16:48.020
in the same location
he found over 100

00:16:48.020 --> 00:16:52.560
additional anatomically
modern human bones and teeth

00:16:52.560 --> 00:16:56.680
in the same formation,
which to me indicates

00:16:56.680 --> 00:17:01.710
a human presence going
back over 400,000 years.

00:17:01.710 --> 00:17:08.130
And I reported on this case
in this paper, which was later

00:17:08.130 --> 00:17:12.079
published in a peer reviewed
conference proceedings volume.

00:17:12.079 --> 00:17:17.180
Recently, just last
year, archaeologists

00:17:17.180 --> 00:17:19.500
reported the discovery
of footprints

00:17:19.500 --> 00:17:24.109
at a place called Happisburgh
in the United Kingdom.

00:17:24.109 --> 00:17:25.880
They were found in
a formation that

00:17:25.880 --> 00:17:30.420
is at least 780,000
years old and is perhaps

00:17:30.420 --> 00:17:33.820
up to a million years old.

00:17:33.820 --> 00:17:39.240
The archaeologist who studied
the footprints published

00:17:39.240 --> 00:17:43.500
results suggesting
they are consistent

00:17:43.500 --> 00:17:46.415
with anatomically
modern human footprints.

00:17:47.640 --> 00:17:50.670
For example, they
studied the foot index,

00:17:50.670 --> 00:17:54.460
which is the width divided
by the length times 100.

00:17:54.460 --> 00:17:59.455
The average for all of the
Happisburgh footprints was 39.

00:18:00.490 --> 00:18:05.470
The average for living Native
American Indians is again, 39.

00:18:05.470 --> 00:18:13.120
The average for living Eskimos
today, the foot index is 38.26.

00:18:13.120 --> 00:18:16.490
And other features
of the footprints

00:18:16.490 --> 00:18:19.810
were consistent with those
of modern human beings.

00:18:19.810 --> 00:18:24.330
Now, of course they
did not believe

00:18:24.330 --> 00:18:28.480
that humans like us
existed at that time.

00:18:28.480 --> 00:18:34.930
They don't think Homo sapiens
existed over 780,000 years ago.

00:18:34.930 --> 00:18:37.770
So they attributed
the footprints

00:18:37.770 --> 00:18:41.540
to a species called
Homo antecessor, an ape

00:18:41.540 --> 00:18:45.430
man that they believe
inhabited Europe at that time.

00:18:45.430 --> 00:18:49.430
But from the evidence itself,
they could just as well

00:18:49.430 --> 00:18:52.730
have been made by
humans like us.

00:18:52.730 --> 00:18:56.940
And there is evidence that
anatomically modern humans

00:18:56.940 --> 00:18:58.095
existed at that time.

00:18:59.440 --> 00:19:03.580
This is the Buenos
Aires Skull, which

00:19:03.580 --> 00:19:07.463
was discovered early in the
20th century in Argentina.

00:19:09.550 --> 00:19:12.860
Researchers were
conducting digging.

00:19:12.860 --> 00:19:15.590
And they had gone
down about 45 feet.

00:19:15.590 --> 00:19:17.710
And they encountered
a solid layer

00:19:17.710 --> 00:19:21.530
of limestone rock
locally known as Tosca.

00:19:21.530 --> 00:19:23.590
And after they broke
through that layer,

00:19:23.590 --> 00:19:27.770
they found a human skull cap
of an anatomically modern

00:19:27.770 --> 00:19:32.880
human type in the
[INAUDIBLE] formation,

00:19:32.880 --> 00:19:38.670
which geologists consider to
be 1 and 1/2 million years old.

00:19:38.670 --> 00:19:41.810
This discovery was reported
to the scientific world

00:19:41.810 --> 00:19:43.980
in the primary
scientific literature

00:19:43.980 --> 00:19:48.640
by the South American
scientist Florentino Ameghino.

00:19:50.590 --> 00:19:54.600
I reported on this
case and some others

00:19:54.600 --> 00:19:57.220
in this paper presented
at a meeting of the World

00:19:57.220 --> 00:20:00.185
Archaeological Congress in
Cape Town, South Africa.

00:20:01.600 --> 00:20:04.290
Many people have heard
of Olduvai Gorge.

00:20:04.290 --> 00:20:07.400
Many important discoveries
have been made there.

00:20:07.400 --> 00:20:10.040
Most people are not aware
of the first discovery that

00:20:10.040 --> 00:20:16.190
was made at Olduvai Gorge
by the German scientist Hans

00:20:16.190 --> 00:20:20.130
Reck, who reported
on it in 1913.

00:20:20.130 --> 00:20:23.510
He found a fairly complete,
anatomically modern

00:20:23.510 --> 00:20:28.220
human skeleton-- that's the
skull cap of it-- buried

00:20:28.220 --> 00:20:31.290
in upper bed II
of Olduvai Gorge.

00:20:32.940 --> 00:20:38.930
Upper bed II of Olduvai
Gorge is between 1.15 and 1.7

00:20:38.930 --> 00:20:40.590
million years ago.

00:20:40.590 --> 00:20:42.250
It was a very
controversial discovery.

00:20:43.670 --> 00:20:46.710
There were decades
of debate about it.

00:20:46.710 --> 00:20:49.030
Many people thought the
debates were finally

00:20:49.030 --> 00:20:54.550
settled in the 1970s when
a German scientist named

00:20:54.550 --> 00:21:00.370
Reiner Protsch did a radiocarbon
test on a fragment of bone

00:21:00.370 --> 00:21:04.290
that he said was
from Reck's skeleton.

00:21:04.290 --> 00:21:08.300
And he got an age of
less than 10,000 years.

00:21:08.300 --> 00:21:11.520
However, I question
the reliability

00:21:11.520 --> 00:21:16.890
of that given that Reiner
Protsch was removed

00:21:16.890 --> 00:21:19.750
from his position at
Frankfurt University

00:21:19.750 --> 00:21:23.620
after an academic
committee there found him

00:21:23.620 --> 00:21:28.130
guilty of having forged
dozens of radiocarbon dates

00:21:28.130 --> 00:21:30.195
during his long career there.

00:21:32.330 --> 00:21:36.300
Another report from the
earlier history of archaeology,

00:21:36.300 --> 00:21:39.920
the jaw, fossil
human jar reported

00:21:39.920 --> 00:21:41.515
by Doctor Robert Coliyer.

00:21:42.650 --> 00:21:44.840
This anatomically
modern human jaw

00:21:44.840 --> 00:21:50.500
was found 16 feet deep in the
Red Crag Formation in England

00:21:50.500 --> 00:21:51.850
at a place called Foxhall.

00:21:53.500 --> 00:21:56.050
The Red Crag
Formation, according

00:21:56.050 --> 00:22:02.210
to modern geological studies,
is between two and three

00:22:02.210 --> 00:22:03.730
million years old.

00:22:05.510 --> 00:22:11.940
In 1979, Mary Leakey announced
the discovery of footprints

00:22:11.940 --> 00:22:15.370
at a place called Laetoli
in the country of Tanzania

00:22:15.370 --> 00:22:16.050
in East Africa.

00:22:17.460 --> 00:22:20.930
According to her
report, the footprints

00:22:20.930 --> 00:22:23.730
were indistinguishable from
modern human footprints.

00:22:25.200 --> 00:22:26.940
Other scientists also agreed.

00:22:26.940 --> 00:22:30.470
Paleontologist Tim White wrote,
"Make no mistake about it.

00:22:30.470 --> 00:22:33.830
They are like modern
human footprints."

00:22:33.830 --> 00:22:37.260
Now, neither Mary
Leakey nor Tim White

00:22:37.260 --> 00:22:41.490
believe those footprints
were made by humans like us.

00:22:41.490 --> 00:22:45.590
They propose they were made
by some type of ape man

00:22:45.590 --> 00:22:49.920
who lived at that time who just
happened to have feet exactly

00:22:49.920 --> 00:22:51.895
like those of
modern human beings.

00:22:53.730 --> 00:22:56.990
Actually, we have the
skeletons of the ape men

00:22:56.990 --> 00:22:59.773
that existed at that
time in eastern Africa.

00:22:59.773 --> 00:23:01.106
They're called Australopithecus.

00:23:02.810 --> 00:23:05.630
And the foot bones
of Australopithecus

00:23:05.630 --> 00:23:06.660
have been discovered.

00:23:06.660 --> 00:23:09.450
And their foot is
not exactly like that

00:23:09.450 --> 00:23:11.700
of a modern human being.

00:23:11.700 --> 00:23:15.290
They have very long toes, sort
of like short human fingers.

00:23:15.290 --> 00:23:18.460
In other words, their feet
were somewhat ape like.

00:23:18.460 --> 00:23:21.530
Actually, the only creature
known to science today

00:23:21.530 --> 00:23:25.940
from skeletal evidence that
has a foot exactly like that

00:23:25.940 --> 00:23:28.520
of a modern human
being is, in fact,

00:23:28.520 --> 00:23:30.365
modern human beings
like ourselves.

00:23:31.420 --> 00:23:34.540
So what did Mary Leakey find?

00:23:34.540 --> 00:23:37.990
I think we have to remain open
to the possibility she found

00:23:37.990 --> 00:23:43.380
evidence that humans
like us were present

00:23:43.380 --> 00:23:46.060
almost four million years ago.

00:23:46.060 --> 00:23:48.120
The footprints were
found in layers

00:23:48.120 --> 00:23:51.740
of solidified volcanic
ash that were dated

00:23:51.740 --> 00:23:58.250
using the potassium argon method
as being 3,700,000 years old.

00:23:58.250 --> 00:24:04.020
I presented evidence
on this case

00:24:04.020 --> 00:24:07.320
at a meeting of the European
Association of Archaeologists

00:24:07.320 --> 00:24:09.660
that was held in England.

00:24:11.730 --> 00:24:14.940
Now, some people might
say, OK, footprints

00:24:14.940 --> 00:24:18.010
are perhaps a little
bit ambiguous.

00:24:18.010 --> 00:24:21.400
It would be better if there
were human skeletal evidence

00:24:21.400 --> 00:24:23.230
almost four million years old.

00:24:24.480 --> 00:24:26.960
Such things have
been reported in

00:24:26.960 --> 00:24:29.040
the primary
scientific literature.

00:24:29.040 --> 00:24:32.450
For example, the
Italian geologist

00:24:32.450 --> 00:24:35.420
Ragazzoni reported
finding human skeletal

00:24:35.420 --> 00:24:39.050
remains at a place called
Castenedolo in northern Italy.

00:24:40.270 --> 00:24:42.130
They were found
in layers of rock

00:24:42.130 --> 00:24:44.270
that modern geologists
consider to be

00:24:44.270 --> 00:24:47.430
about four million years old.

00:24:47.430 --> 00:24:49.530
I went to the village
of Castenedolo.

00:24:49.530 --> 00:24:50.950
I met this gentleman there.

00:24:50.950 --> 00:24:56.230
And he gave me a copy of a very
rare geological report dealing

00:24:56.230 --> 00:24:58.060
with this discovery.

00:24:58.060 --> 00:25:00.210
And from the information
in the report,

00:25:00.210 --> 00:25:03.070
we were able to
locate the place where

00:25:03.070 --> 00:25:04.365
the discoveries were made.

00:25:06.330 --> 00:25:11.810
Now, the current explanation
of these discoveries

00:25:11.810 --> 00:25:15.220
is, well, it's not
really possible

00:25:15.220 --> 00:25:18.530
that you could have anatomically
modern human skeletons

00:25:18.530 --> 00:25:21.860
in layers of rock four
million years old.

00:25:21.860 --> 00:25:27.860
So the proposal is that
maybe about 4,000 years ago,

00:25:27.860 --> 00:25:30.260
somebody died on the surface.

00:25:30.260 --> 00:25:35.800
His friends dug a grave
and put the skeleton down

00:25:35.800 --> 00:25:37.270
in that ancient layer of rock.

00:25:37.270 --> 00:25:42.470
And that's why
you think you have

00:25:42.470 --> 00:25:45.150
a human skeleton four
million years old.

00:25:45.150 --> 00:25:47.210
Things like this can
happen, technically.

00:25:47.210 --> 00:25:49.650
It's called intrusive burial.

00:25:49.650 --> 00:25:53.960
However, if you look at
Ragazzoni's original reports

00:25:53.960 --> 00:25:57.650
in the Italian
language, which I did,

00:25:57.650 --> 00:26:00.500
he says-- because
even at the time,

00:26:00.500 --> 00:26:02.330
he was a professional geologist.

00:26:02.330 --> 00:26:06.480
He was aware of the possibility
of intrusive burial.

00:26:06.480 --> 00:26:08.540
He said, if it had been
an intrusive burial,

00:26:08.540 --> 00:26:10.590
the layers of rock
above the skeleton

00:26:10.590 --> 00:26:12.490
would have been undisturbed.

00:26:12.490 --> 00:26:15.640
However, he found
that the layers

00:26:15.640 --> 00:26:20.010
of rock above the skeleton were
all intact and undisturbed.

00:26:20.010 --> 00:26:24.490
Actually, he said each layer has
its own micro-stratigraphy that

00:26:24.490 --> 00:26:25.230
was undisturbed.

00:26:27.010 --> 00:26:31.850
So I take this as evidence
for human presence going back

00:26:31.850 --> 00:26:33.385
over four million years.

00:26:34.410 --> 00:26:37.600
This is Carlos Ribeiro, who
was the chief government

00:26:37.600 --> 00:26:40.430
geologist of Portugal.

00:26:40.430 --> 00:26:43.140
He found hundreds
of human artifacts

00:26:43.140 --> 00:26:44.455
in his country of Portugal.

00:26:45.500 --> 00:26:49.080
He found them in layers
of rock that date back

00:26:49.080 --> 00:26:52.500
to the early Miocene
Period, which

00:26:52.500 --> 00:26:56.170
means they would be about 20
million years old according

00:26:56.170 --> 00:26:57.615
to today's understanding.

00:26:59.250 --> 00:27:02.630
He, as a professional geologist,
he said they cannot have come

00:27:02.630 --> 00:27:05.940
into those layers from any
higher level through any

00:27:05.940 --> 00:27:09.865
fissure, or crack, or all
the usual kinds of counter

00:27:09.865 --> 00:27:10.406
explanations.

00:27:11.950 --> 00:27:16.410
He displayed the artifacts
in the Museum of Geology

00:27:16.410 --> 00:27:18.120
in Lisbon.

00:27:18.120 --> 00:27:21.381
But if you go there today,
you won't see them on display

00:27:21.381 --> 00:27:21.880
anymore.

00:27:21.880 --> 00:27:25.300
They're kept in the
cabinets behind me.

00:27:25.300 --> 00:27:27.780
But I was able to get
permission from the directors

00:27:27.780 --> 00:27:31.740
of the museum to
study and photograph

00:27:31.740 --> 00:27:36.140
some of these human artifacts
from the early Miocene period.

00:27:36.140 --> 00:27:40.400
I also carefully studied
Ribeiro's original maps,

00:27:40.400 --> 00:27:42.760
and field notes,
and correspondence

00:27:42.760 --> 00:27:44.030
of the museum archives.

00:27:45.120 --> 00:27:48.690
And then I went into the
countryside of Portugal

00:27:48.690 --> 00:27:51.030
and I relocated
some of the sites

00:27:51.030 --> 00:27:53.310
where he made his discoveries.

00:27:53.310 --> 00:27:54.970
This is the quarry
at Murganheira.

00:27:57.400 --> 00:28:00.940
And he found human
artifacts there

00:28:00.940 --> 00:28:03.937
in lower Miocene formations.

00:28:03.937 --> 00:28:04.770
This is one of them.

00:28:04.770 --> 00:28:05.850
It's a flint artifact.

00:28:06.910 --> 00:28:08.920
It's interesting what happened.

00:28:08.920 --> 00:28:11.690
When Ribeiro was
alive, the artifacts

00:28:11.690 --> 00:28:17.240
were displayed in the museum
with labels showing a lower

00:28:17.240 --> 00:28:21.030
Miocene age for them,
about 20 million years.

00:28:21.030 --> 00:28:23.870
After he died, his
colleagues in the museum

00:28:23.870 --> 00:28:25.015
did something interesting.

00:28:26.090 --> 00:28:28.450
They left the
artifacts on display,

00:28:28.450 --> 00:28:31.070
but they wrote new
labels for all of them.

00:28:31.070 --> 00:28:33.630
This is the new label they
wrote for the artifact I just

00:28:33.630 --> 00:28:34.340
showed you.

00:28:35.880 --> 00:28:39.390
Second line gives the
age-- Paleolitico Superior,

00:28:39.390 --> 00:28:41.210
Upper Paleolithic Period.

00:28:42.480 --> 00:28:46.180
According to geologists
today, that period in Europe

00:28:46.180 --> 00:28:49.720
goes back about 20,000 years.

00:28:49.720 --> 00:28:50.860
So it's interesting.

00:28:52.130 --> 00:28:54.400
Ribeiro's colleagues
thought 20 million years,

00:28:54.400 --> 00:28:55.920
that's clearly impossible.

00:28:55.920 --> 00:28:59.080
20,000 years, that
sounds about right

00:28:59.080 --> 00:29:00.780
for discoveries like this.

00:29:01.870 --> 00:29:04.770
So they just wrote new labels
for all of the artifacts.

00:29:05.870 --> 00:29:09.500
Now, the next generation
of officials in the museum

00:29:09.500 --> 00:29:11.460
just put the entire
collection away.

00:29:11.460 --> 00:29:16.240
And I'm the first researcher
to see these things in over 50

00:29:16.240 --> 00:29:17.600
years.

00:29:17.600 --> 00:29:21.000
I presented a paper on
this case at a meeting

00:29:21.000 --> 00:29:24.280
of the European Association
of Archaeologists

00:29:24.280 --> 00:29:28.210
that was held in Lisbon,
Portugal in the year 2000.

00:29:28.210 --> 00:29:33.340
That paper was later
published in a peer reviewed

00:29:33.340 --> 00:29:37.490
scientific journal from
Europe, "The Journal of Iberian

00:29:37.490 --> 00:29:40.740
Archaeology."

00:29:40.740 --> 00:29:42.590
A case that's
always fascinated me

00:29:42.590 --> 00:29:45.190
has been the California
gold mine discoveries.

00:29:45.190 --> 00:29:47.650
Gold was discovered
in California.

00:29:47.650 --> 00:29:50.870
And miners went to places
like Table Mountain

00:29:50.870 --> 00:29:53.180
in Tuolumne County near Sonora.

00:29:53.180 --> 00:29:55.070
Actually not too far from here.

00:29:56.440 --> 00:29:59.310
And deep inside the
tunnels, the miners

00:29:59.310 --> 00:30:02.630
found human bones
and human artifacts.

00:30:02.630 --> 00:30:06.780
For example, they found
many of these stone mortars

00:30:06.780 --> 00:30:07.640
and pestles.

00:30:09.940 --> 00:30:11.820
What makes them so
interesting to me

00:30:11.820 --> 00:30:14.070
is they were found in
layers of solid rock

00:30:14.070 --> 00:30:16.840
that date to the early part
of the geological period

00:30:16.840 --> 00:30:19.370
called Eocene, which
means they would

00:30:19.370 --> 00:30:23.700
be about 50 million years old.

00:30:23.700 --> 00:30:27.010
Some of the details about the
dating of the discoveries.

00:30:27.010 --> 00:30:31.800
It was done in modern times
using the potassium argon

00:30:31.800 --> 00:30:34.730
method and analyzing
the plant and animal

00:30:34.730 --> 00:30:38.000
fossils found in
those layers of rock.

00:30:38.000 --> 00:30:40.970
These discoveries
were originally

00:30:40.970 --> 00:30:44.680
reported to the scientific
world by Doctor JD Whitney, who

00:30:44.680 --> 00:30:48.686
was the chief government
geologist of California.

00:30:49.740 --> 00:30:55.540
His report was published by
Harvard University in the year

00:30:55.540 --> 00:30:56.380
1880.

00:30:56.380 --> 00:31:00.970
But we don't hear very much
about these discoveries today

00:31:00.970 --> 00:31:04.120
because of the process
of knowledge filtration

00:31:04.120 --> 00:31:04.980
that I mentioned.

00:31:04.980 --> 00:31:08.310
This is the anthropologist
William Holmes,

00:31:08.310 --> 00:31:10.460
who worked with the
Smithsonian Institution.

00:31:10.460 --> 00:31:15.470
And he wrote in his report, "If
Doctor Whitney had understood

00:31:15.470 --> 00:31:20.020
the theory of
human evolution, he

00:31:20.020 --> 00:31:22.630
would not have published
those discoveries."

00:31:22.630 --> 00:31:26.390
In other words, he would've
known that humans could not

00:31:26.390 --> 00:31:29.060
possibly have
existed at that time.

00:31:30.090 --> 00:31:33.620
A few years ago,
I was a consultant

00:31:33.620 --> 00:31:36.580
for a television documentary
called "The Mysterious

00:31:36.580 --> 00:31:38.676
Origins of Man"
that aired on NBC.

00:31:41.160 --> 00:31:44.670
And the producer
of this documentary

00:31:44.670 --> 00:31:47.120
had read my book,
"Forbidden Archeology"

00:31:47.120 --> 00:31:49.875
and wanted to include some
cases in the documentary.

00:31:51.080 --> 00:31:54.690
I told him he should go to
the Museum of Anthropology

00:31:54.690 --> 00:31:56.980
at the University of
California at Berkeley

00:31:56.980 --> 00:32:00.780
because artifacts from
the California gold mines

00:32:00.780 --> 00:32:02.030
were still in that collection.

00:32:03.160 --> 00:32:06.510
And the museum officials
refused to allow

00:32:06.510 --> 00:32:10.100
him to see the artifacts.

00:32:10.100 --> 00:32:12.440
Anyways, we were able
to get some photographs

00:32:12.440 --> 00:32:14.250
of the artifacts
that Doctor Whitney

00:32:14.250 --> 00:32:16.020
had taken in the 19th century.

00:32:16.020 --> 00:32:21.250
It was interesting what happened
when this documentary aired.

00:32:21.250 --> 00:32:25.590
Actually, many
scientists were outraged

00:32:25.590 --> 00:32:31.680
and they wanted the FCC to
investigate NBC, censor NBC,

00:32:31.680 --> 00:32:37.790
fine NBC millions of dollars for
having aired this documentary.

00:32:37.790 --> 00:32:42.760
And I'm happy to say the FCC
didn't do any of those things.

00:32:42.760 --> 00:32:46.210
But it was interesting that
such attempts were made.

00:32:46.210 --> 00:32:48.860
Later, I went back
to the museum myself.

00:32:48.860 --> 00:32:52.230
And I personally was given
access to the discoveries,

00:32:52.230 --> 00:32:54.030
and they are still there.

00:32:54.030 --> 00:33:00.260
They also went out to
Table Mountain near Sonora.

00:33:00.260 --> 00:33:04.260
And we were able to relocate
some of the old 19th century

00:33:04.260 --> 00:33:08.150
gold mining tunnels where these
discoveries were originally

00:33:08.150 --> 00:33:09.180
made.

00:33:09.180 --> 00:33:12.750
I reported on this case at
this meeting of the World

00:33:12.750 --> 00:33:19.150
Archaeological Congress that was
held in Washington, DC in 2003.

00:33:19.150 --> 00:33:24.070
So how far back in time can
we go with evidence like this?

00:33:24.070 --> 00:33:27.290
In 1862, a scientific
journal called

00:33:27.290 --> 00:33:29.890
"The Geologist" published
an interesting report.

00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:33.820
An anatomically
modern human skeleton

00:33:33.820 --> 00:33:36.480
was found 90 feet
below the surface

00:33:36.480 --> 00:33:41.050
of the ground in Macoupin
County in the state of Illinois

00:33:41.050 --> 00:33:42.390
near St. Louis.

00:33:43.880 --> 00:33:46.120
According to the report,
above the skeleton

00:33:46.120 --> 00:33:50.750
was a thick layer of slate
rock that was unbroken.

00:33:50.750 --> 00:33:54.280
That's an important detail,
because it kind of rules out

00:33:54.280 --> 00:33:56.630
the intrusive burial hypothesis.

00:33:58.510 --> 00:34:00.940
This report from
"Scientific American"

00:34:00.940 --> 00:34:04.080
tells of a beautiful,
metallic-- whoops.

00:34:04.080 --> 00:34:05.740
I wanted one more detail.

00:34:06.800 --> 00:34:09.370
According to modern
geologists, the layer

00:34:09.370 --> 00:34:13.420
where the skeleton was found
is about 300 million years old.

00:34:16.159 --> 00:34:18.350
This report from
"Scientific American"

00:34:18.350 --> 00:34:20.550
tells of a beautiful
metallic vase

00:34:20.550 --> 00:34:25.600
that was found 15 feet deep in
solid rock in Dorchester, which

00:34:25.600 --> 00:34:27.800
is in the Boston area.

00:34:27.800 --> 00:34:31.210
According to modern
geological reports,

00:34:31.210 --> 00:34:34.760
the age of a formation at
that location and depth

00:34:34.760 --> 00:34:38.070
is about 600 million years
from the Cambrian Period.

00:34:39.139 --> 00:34:42.830
Now, I could actually keep
you here for days, and days,

00:34:42.830 --> 00:34:45.719
and days because
there are hundreds

00:34:45.719 --> 00:34:49.315
of reports like this in the
primary scientific literature.

00:34:51.080 --> 00:34:52.710
I'm not going to do that.

00:34:52.710 --> 00:34:56.570
But I'll make some
concluding remarks.

00:34:56.570 --> 00:34:59.860
The significance
of this evidence

00:34:59.860 --> 00:35:02.110
would be that it
would contradict

00:35:02.110 --> 00:35:05.850
the now dominant ideas
about human origins.

00:35:07.480 --> 00:35:10.960
And this was actually
recognized by one

00:35:10.960 --> 00:35:14.650
of the architects of the
current paradigm, Doctor William

00:35:14.650 --> 00:35:17.860
Howells of Harvard, who
wrote to me after he

00:35:17.860 --> 00:35:19.890
read "Forbidden Archeology."

00:35:19.890 --> 00:35:22.560
And he said a few
things about it.

00:35:22.560 --> 00:35:24.990
He said, "'Forbidden
Archaeology' represents much

00:35:24.990 --> 00:35:28.690
careful effort in critically
assembling published

00:35:28.690 --> 00:35:29.410
materials."

00:35:29.410 --> 00:35:32.560
I thought it was nice
that he recognized that.

00:35:32.560 --> 00:35:36.220
And then he said, "Most
of us, mistakenly or not,

00:35:36.220 --> 00:35:39.130
see human evolution with
man emerging rather late."

00:35:39.130 --> 00:35:40.505
And that's the actual fact.

00:35:42.550 --> 00:35:46.540
Most scientists actually
do see things that way.

00:35:48.030 --> 00:35:52.850
And he went on to say, "To have
modern human beings appearing

00:35:52.850 --> 00:35:56.100
a great deal earlier would be
devastating to the whole theory

00:35:56.100 --> 00:35:57.490
of evolution."

00:35:57.490 --> 00:36:03.480
So that's what he saw as the
impact of this kind of evidence

00:36:03.480 --> 00:36:06.670
if it were to be
taken as genuine.

00:36:07.710 --> 00:36:11.086
Now, not everybody is willing
to do that, admittedly.

00:36:12.610 --> 00:36:16.450
Now, another
interesting statement

00:36:16.450 --> 00:36:18.360
about "Forbidden
Archaeology" was

00:36:18.360 --> 00:36:22.130
made by archaeologist Tim
Murray in his review published

00:36:22.130 --> 00:36:27.090
in "British Journal for
History of Science."

00:36:27.090 --> 00:36:30.515
Now, Murray is
one of my critics.

00:36:31.940 --> 00:36:38.670
And still, even though
he's not really prepared

00:36:38.670 --> 00:36:41.700
to accept my conclusion, he
has some interesting things

00:36:41.700 --> 00:36:44.505
to say that I think
are worth repeating.

00:36:45.560 --> 00:36:48.040
He said, "'Forbidden
Archeology,'" quote,

00:36:48.040 --> 00:36:51.080
"provides the historian of
archaeology with a useful

00:36:51.080 --> 00:36:54.940
compendium of case studies
in the history and sociology

00:36:54.940 --> 00:36:58.780
of scientific knowledge, which
can be used to foster debate

00:36:58.780 --> 00:37:02.420
within archaeology about how
to describe the epistemology

00:37:02.420 --> 00:37:04.310
of one's discipline."

00:37:04.310 --> 00:37:06.880
And that's actually
what I was trying

00:37:06.880 --> 00:37:14.190
to do in putting that book
together, to foster debate

00:37:14.190 --> 00:37:17.430
within archaeology about the
epistemology of the discipline.

00:37:18.500 --> 00:37:22.880
And to see this acknowledged
in the professional literature

00:37:22.880 --> 00:37:24.650
was kind of interesting.

00:37:24.650 --> 00:37:28.660
Now, he went on to say,
"'Forbidden Archaeology' is

00:37:28.660 --> 00:37:31.840
designed to demolish the case
for biological and cultural

00:37:31.840 --> 00:37:36.700
evolution and to advance the
cause of a Vedic alternative."

00:37:36.700 --> 00:37:38.825
Now, I plead guilty
to that indictment.

00:37:40.290 --> 00:37:45.900
And it's at this point that many
in the world of science today

00:37:45.900 --> 00:37:47.985
are really going to
have strong objections

00:37:47.985 --> 00:37:50.590
to the kinds of
things that I do.

00:37:50.590 --> 00:37:54.760
This mention of Vedic
alternative, in other words

00:37:54.760 --> 00:37:57.540
some alternative
that has its roots

00:37:57.540 --> 00:37:59.620
in some religious
or spiritual idea.

00:38:01.310 --> 00:38:03.170
According to many in
the world of science

00:38:03.170 --> 00:38:05.510
today, this is
completely verboten.

00:38:05.510 --> 00:38:09.530
That's why I called the
book "Forbidden Archeology."

00:38:09.530 --> 00:38:16.130
But it's interesting what Tim
Murray had to say about that.

00:38:16.130 --> 00:38:21.770
He said, "The 'dominant
paradigm' has changed

00:38:21.770 --> 00:38:22.790
and is changing.

00:38:22.790 --> 00:38:25.880
And practitioners
openly debate issues

00:38:25.880 --> 00:38:28.860
which go right to the conceptual
core of the discipline.

00:38:30.240 --> 00:38:33.070
Whether the Vedas have
a role to play in this

00:38:33.070 --> 00:38:36.070
is up to the individual
scientist's concern."

00:38:36.070 --> 00:38:39.950
And I think that's an
enlightened attitude

00:38:39.950 --> 00:38:41.565
that I can support.

00:38:42.600 --> 00:38:49.520
No ban, but it's just
up to each individual

00:38:49.520 --> 00:38:51.890
to make up their
mind whether or not

00:38:51.890 --> 00:38:56.470
they're going to try to do
something like I'm doing

00:38:56.470 --> 00:38:57.400
or agree with it.

00:39:01.310 --> 00:39:04.755
Gets you into a whole discussion
about religion and science.

00:39:06.240 --> 00:39:11.330
Now, I'm going to close
with some of my experiences

00:39:11.330 --> 00:39:13.750
in presenting this kind
of thing at university

00:39:13.750 --> 00:39:15.830
audiences around the world.

00:39:15.830 --> 00:39:18.920
I've spoken at hundreds of
universities around the world.

00:39:18.920 --> 00:39:22.202
My books are now in about
25 different languages.

00:39:22.202 --> 00:39:23.160
One of them is Russian.

00:39:24.170 --> 00:39:26.960
So I've lectured at a lot
of universities in Russia,

00:39:26.960 --> 00:39:29.350
from Vladivostok to
Saint Petersburg.

00:39:29.350 --> 00:39:31.085
And usually, the
lectures go fine.

00:39:34.200 --> 00:39:37.170
At this particular university,
the Tyumen State University,

00:39:37.170 --> 00:39:38.670
there was a little
bit of a problem.

00:39:38.670 --> 00:39:40.920
Some professors there
had invited me to speak.

00:39:42.280 --> 00:39:44.530
And a lecture was scheduled.

00:39:44.530 --> 00:39:46.940
But when other faculty
members found out

00:39:46.940 --> 00:39:48.710
that I was being
invited to speak,

00:39:48.710 --> 00:39:51.780
they approached
the administration

00:39:51.780 --> 00:39:54.990
of the university and
said, we can't have this.

00:39:54.990 --> 00:39:58.953
We shouldn't allow this person
to speak at our university.

00:40:01.210 --> 00:40:04.970
First of all, he's
contradicting a dominant theory.

00:40:04.970 --> 00:40:07.820
And second, and
even more damningly,

00:40:07.820 --> 00:40:13.010
he's doing it from some Vedic
spiritual kind of perspective.

00:40:14.970 --> 00:40:18.680
So the president of the
university cancelled

00:40:18.680 --> 00:40:19.840
the lecture.

00:40:19.840 --> 00:40:23.490
The professors who invited me
and wanted to hear me speak

00:40:23.490 --> 00:40:27.170
went to the president and tried
to get him to change his mind.

00:40:27.170 --> 00:40:29.680
But the pressure from the
other side was just too big,

00:40:29.680 --> 00:40:31.120
so the lecture was cancelled.

00:40:32.310 --> 00:40:34.520
So then, the professors
who invited me

00:40:34.520 --> 00:40:37.395
went to the local branch of the
Russian Academy of Sciences.

00:40:37.395 --> 00:40:39.870
And they spoke to
the director there.

00:40:39.870 --> 00:40:41.990
And he said, OK,
if they won't let

00:40:41.990 --> 00:40:44.970
him speak at the university,
he can speak here

00:40:44.970 --> 00:40:47.240
at the Russian Academy
of Science building.

00:40:48.400 --> 00:40:52.510
So they had buses bring
students and professors

00:40:52.510 --> 00:40:55.581
from the university to the
Russian Academy of Science

00:40:55.581 --> 00:40:56.080
building.

00:40:57.110 --> 00:41:00.860
And the professors who invited
me said, more people came then

00:41:00.860 --> 00:41:06.105
would've come if the lecture
had been held at the university.

00:41:07.640 --> 00:41:12.140
And then the next year,
something interesting happened.

00:41:12.140 --> 00:41:15.970
I went back to the
same university,

00:41:15.970 --> 00:41:20.430
and I was able to speak
at the biology department

00:41:20.430 --> 00:41:21.260
there no problem.

00:41:22.300 --> 00:41:25.090
I guess they just thought,
better let him talk

00:41:25.090 --> 00:41:27.910
and let people just make
up their minds about what

00:41:27.910 --> 00:41:28.480
he's saying.

00:41:29.917 --> 00:41:30.750
They're intelligent.

00:41:31.900 --> 00:41:34.935
They'll be able to figure out
if they can agree or not agree.

00:41:34.935 --> 00:41:37.185
It's not going to be the end
of the world if he talks.

00:41:38.470 --> 00:41:41.350
These are some of my works--
"The Forbidden Archaeologist,"

00:41:41.350 --> 00:41:44.100
"Forbidden Archaeology," "Hidden
History of the Human Race,"

00:41:44.100 --> 00:41:48.790
"Human Devolution," "My
Science, My Religion."

00:41:48.790 --> 00:41:51.203
Some contact information.

00:41:54.790 --> 00:42:01.160
And if you do like the kinds
of things you've heard today

00:42:01.160 --> 00:42:03.110
and are interested
in hearing more,

00:42:03.110 --> 00:42:05.330
you may want to
come on this cruise

00:42:05.330 --> 00:42:09.960
where I'm the speaker
in June, 2015.

00:42:09.960 --> 00:42:15.305
Go up and see the glaciers
and hear some weird stuff.

00:42:18.080 --> 00:42:23.950
So I have ended five minutes
before I intended to.

00:42:25.487 --> 00:42:28.896
