have valid,
scientific reasons why

00:47:46.400 --> 00:47:47.970
they're refuting your evidence?

00:47:48.980 --> 00:47:51.640
MICHAEL CREMO: Normally--
I mean, everybody's

00:47:51.640 --> 00:47:55.430
going to have to make up their
own minds about these things.

00:47:55.430 --> 00:47:59.420
What I try to do in
"Forbidden Archeology"

00:47:59.420 --> 00:48:08.790
was provide in each case all
of the different opinions,

00:48:08.790 --> 00:48:10.700
all sides of the
question, and leave it up

00:48:10.700 --> 00:48:13.470
to the reader to make up
their own mind whether they

00:48:13.470 --> 00:48:16.330
think it's valid or not.

00:48:16.330 --> 00:48:23.880
Typically, the
reactions are to suggest

00:48:23.880 --> 00:48:27.385
first of all, it's old evidence.

00:48:29.100 --> 00:48:31.485
In other words, but
this is very selective.

00:48:32.950 --> 00:48:36.440
It's the idea that--
kind of like a milk

00:48:36.440 --> 00:48:40.090
carton, scientific evidence
got an expiration date.

00:48:41.310 --> 00:48:44.610
That any science
conducted before midnight,

00:48:44.610 --> 00:48:49.390
January 1, 1900
somehow has expired.

00:48:52.710 --> 00:48:56.360
But I noticed that those who
make that type of criticism

00:48:56.360 --> 00:48:59.820
are applying it
very selectively,

00:48:59.820 --> 00:49:03.580
because the standard
textbooks of archaeology

00:49:03.580 --> 00:49:05.750
are full of
discoveries that were

00:49:05.750 --> 00:49:10.855
made in the 19th century,
early 20th century.

00:49:13.350 --> 00:49:16.830
So it can't just be that
just because something

00:49:16.830 --> 00:49:20.060
is from the earlier
history of archaeology,

00:49:20.060 --> 00:49:21.170
it has to be wrong.

00:49:22.200 --> 00:49:26.280
Another category
of objection has

00:49:26.280 --> 00:49:31.350
to do with lists of ways in
which something could be wrong.

00:49:32.490 --> 00:49:35.070
It's possible there was a hoax.

00:49:35.070 --> 00:49:38.830
It's possible it could've
slipped in through a fissure.

00:49:38.830 --> 00:49:44.050
It's possible that the original
investigator made a mistake.

00:49:44.050 --> 00:49:46.445
It's possible this,
it's possible that.

00:49:47.570 --> 00:49:50.960
My general response to
that category of criticism

00:49:50.960 --> 00:49:54.120
is everything is
certainly possible.

00:49:54.120 --> 00:49:57.590
But if you're going to
proceed in a scientific way,

00:49:57.590 --> 00:50:02.120
you should be able to show that
in this particular location,

00:50:02.120 --> 00:50:03.290
there was a fissure.

00:50:03.290 --> 00:50:07.350
There were artifacts
on the surface that

00:50:07.350 --> 00:50:09.800
resemble those that were
found at that level.

00:50:09.800 --> 00:50:13.790
And there definitely was a way
they could have got down there.

00:50:13.790 --> 00:50:21.670
So that's another
category of objection.

00:50:21.670 --> 00:50:26.130
And of course, I'm willing
to engage on that level.

00:50:26.130 --> 00:50:27.820
And it's one of
the things I hope

00:50:27.820 --> 00:50:34.610
to accomplish with the book is
to have a second look at some

00:50:34.610 --> 00:50:35.740
of these things.

00:50:35.740 --> 00:50:39.070
And if there are
objections, raise them.

00:50:41.970 --> 00:50:44.650
AUDIENCE: My question
is you mentioned

00:50:44.650 --> 00:50:50.300
about a guy that in 19th century
found a jawbone in a layer that

00:50:50.300 --> 00:50:52.970
was 400,000 year old.

00:50:52.970 --> 00:50:55.035
How did they knew
in 19th century

00:50:55.035 --> 00:50:58.650
that this particular
layer was that old

00:50:58.650 --> 00:51:00.040
without any dating methods?

00:51:00.040 --> 00:51:00.790
MICHAEL CREMO: OK.

00:51:00.790 --> 00:51:01.920
It's a good question.

00:51:03.500 --> 00:51:05.720
What I said, if you
listened carefully,

00:51:05.720 --> 00:51:09.032
was that according
to modern geologists,

00:51:09.032 --> 00:51:12.880
the layer is a certain
number of years old.

00:51:14.590 --> 00:51:21.300
At that time, they characterized
things in another way,

00:51:21.300 --> 00:51:26.620
not using necessarily
years, but characterizing

00:51:26.620 --> 00:51:33.350
things as early Pleistocene,
early middle Pleistocene,

00:51:33.350 --> 00:51:34.790
and things of that sort.

00:51:35.920 --> 00:51:46.440
So if you translate those
terms to the modern dates that

00:51:46.440 --> 00:51:50.310
are attached to those
terms, it works out.

00:51:51.830 --> 00:51:56.980
So they would have
said, that jawbone

00:51:56.980 --> 00:52:02.830
was found in an early
Pleistocene layer, which

00:52:02.830 --> 00:52:08.375
would mean it would have
to be several hundred

00:52:08.375 --> 00:52:10.895
thousand years old at least.

00:52:12.430 --> 00:52:14.390
That's why I went by the modern.

00:52:14.390 --> 00:52:18.530
To give an age in years, I
went by the modern geological

00:52:18.530 --> 00:52:22.410
dating of those
layers at Abbeville.

00:52:23.610 --> 00:52:26.700
For example,
Ribeiro, he would've

00:52:26.700 --> 00:52:31.160
said these stone tools
are early Miocene.

00:52:32.340 --> 00:52:35.940
Now, in the 19th century,
the conception of the Miocene

00:52:35.940 --> 00:52:36.650
was there.

00:52:36.650 --> 00:52:40.800
But it wouldn't be exactly
the number of years

00:52:40.800 --> 00:52:43.270
that we now attach to it.

00:52:43.270 --> 00:52:45.630
But still, it was
considered to be very old

00:52:45.630 --> 00:52:49.950
in terms of the succession
of geological layers.

00:52:49.950 --> 00:52:57.140
But just for current reference,
I give the estimates in years

00:52:57.140 --> 00:53:01.800
that modern geologists have
determined for these layers.

00:53:01.800 --> 00:53:04.870
The same with Doctor
Whitney's report.

00:53:04.870 --> 00:53:10.630
He would have said, these layers
are from the Pliocene Period,

00:53:10.630 --> 00:53:13.285
which is an old
geological period.

00:53:15.180 --> 00:53:18.360
Now, the layers that
he considered Pliocene

00:53:18.360 --> 00:53:20.300
are considered to be Eocene.

00:53:20.300 --> 00:53:24.865
And the age for them is between
30 and 50 million years.

00:53:28.870 --> 00:53:30.800
In the 19th century,
they wouldn't

00:53:30.800 --> 00:53:34.760
be using the same number
of years that we do.

00:53:34.760 --> 00:53:38.510
But they had a concept
still that, in terms

00:53:38.510 --> 00:53:42.430
of the system they were
using, it was older.

00:53:42.430 --> 00:53:45.490
They expected human
beings like us

00:53:45.490 --> 00:53:51.710
to appear only in the very
latest, very recent Pleistocene

00:53:51.710 --> 00:53:52.210
Period.

00:53:55.000 --> 00:54:01.220
So if it was from the middle
or the early Pleistocene,

00:54:01.220 --> 00:54:03.550
that would be
anomalous for them.

00:54:06.060 --> 00:54:06.755
Is that helping?

00:54:08.037 --> 00:54:09.620
AUDIENCE: Let's say
it's 19th century.

00:54:09.620 --> 00:54:12.650
We dig a hole in the ground
and we find few layers.

00:54:12.650 --> 00:54:16.300
And they somehow decided,
oh, this layer is younger,

00:54:16.300 --> 00:54:19.410
this is older
based on the depth.

00:54:19.410 --> 00:54:21.790
But then they put
some dates to it.

00:54:21.790 --> 00:54:26.280
And I think it's almost
the same as right now.

00:54:26.280 --> 00:54:29.690
We also have layers and they
have dates attached to them.

00:54:29.690 --> 00:54:34.430
And my concern is that maybe we
just attached the dates badly.

00:54:34.430 --> 00:54:35.970
How do you know exactly?

00:54:35.970 --> 00:54:38.370
Just like they might be
wrong about the dates

00:54:38.370 --> 00:54:40.770
in 19th century, they might
be wrong about the dates

00:54:40.770 --> 00:54:41.490
right now.

00:54:41.490 --> 00:54:43.130
MICHAEL CREMO: I'm
prepared to accept

00:54:43.130 --> 00:54:47.850
that if we want to say we
don't know how old anything is,

00:54:47.850 --> 00:54:52.430
really, and all the dating
methods are unreliable,

00:54:52.430 --> 00:54:54.030
we could certainly do that.

00:54:54.030 --> 00:54:56.130
That's one approach to take.

00:54:56.130 --> 00:54:58.530
The approach, however,
that I've taken

00:54:58.530 --> 00:55:00.420
is you have to have
some kind of framework

00:55:00.420 --> 00:55:01.960
for discussing things.

00:55:03.430 --> 00:55:07.786
And I'm addressing an audience
of geologists, archaeologists,

00:55:07.786 --> 00:55:08.452
paleontologists.

00:55:10.270 --> 00:55:15.530
And my way of creating a frame
of reference for the discussion

00:55:15.530 --> 00:55:19.280
is to say, according to
methods that you consider

00:55:19.280 --> 00:55:24.520
reliable-- radiocarbon dating,
potassium argon dating, uranium

00:55:24.520 --> 00:55:27.810
series dating, zircon
fission-track dating--

00:55:27.810 --> 00:55:32.350
these layers belong to
this geological period,

00:55:32.350 --> 00:55:37.730
which you consider to be
millions of years old.

00:55:37.730 --> 00:55:42.110
Now, if you want to take the
approach that, well, nothing

00:55:42.110 --> 00:55:44.840
is reliable and we
don't know anything

00:55:44.840 --> 00:55:47.290
about the real age
of anything, that's

00:55:47.290 --> 00:55:50.580
certainly an approach
that could be taken.

00:55:50.580 --> 00:55:58.670
And some out in the world--
say if you're a young Earth

00:55:58.670 --> 00:56:03.210
Christian creationist who
believes that the Earth is

00:56:03.210 --> 00:56:07.870
no older than
10,000 years, you're

00:56:07.870 --> 00:56:11.340
going to be very critical of all
the different dating methods.

00:56:11.340 --> 00:56:16.190
And that may be the
way that such a person

00:56:16.190 --> 00:56:18.150
would approach this.

00:56:18.150 --> 00:56:21.680
The Vedic time scales
are more or less

00:56:21.680 --> 00:56:25.260
consistent with the
modern scientific time

00:56:25.260 --> 00:56:29.190
scales for the universe, and
the Earth, and things like that.

00:56:30.260 --> 00:56:34.280
So perhaps I'm not
motivated sufficiently

00:56:34.280 --> 00:56:39.451
to try to dismiss all the
different scientific dating

00:56:39.451 --> 00:56:39.950
methods.

00:56:42.040 --> 00:56:45.600
AUDIENCE: Are there
cases where the age

00:56:45.600 --> 00:56:50.740
of the layer and the dating,
some kind of scientific dating,

00:56:50.740 --> 00:56:56.315
of the actual bones, say, is
the same and is very ancient?

00:57:03.010 --> 00:57:07.330
MICHAEL CREMO: Well, there are--
if we're talking about bone,

00:57:07.330 --> 00:57:10.090
there are only a
very few methods

00:57:10.090 --> 00:57:15.700
that can be used to
directly date bone.

00:57:15.700 --> 00:57:17.460
There's the radiocarbon method.

00:57:17.460 --> 00:57:20.460
But that works only
back to about 50,000

00:57:20.460 --> 00:57:23.030
or 100,000 years at
most because it's

00:57:23.030 --> 00:57:29.780
based on the decay
of carbon-14, which

00:57:29.780 --> 00:57:32.350
has a half life of
about 5,000 years.

00:57:32.350 --> 00:57:35.180
And after about 20
half lives, there's

00:57:35.180 --> 00:57:36.225
nothing left to measure.

00:57:37.990 --> 00:57:40.490
There's the uranium
series method,

00:57:40.490 --> 00:57:45.430
which is based on
the decay of uranium

00:57:45.430 --> 00:57:47.745
to different daughter isotopes.

00:57:49.120 --> 00:57:51.990
And by measuring the
ratios of those isotopes

00:57:51.990 --> 00:57:55.280
and making certain assumptions
about intake and outflow

00:57:55.280 --> 00:58:02.350
of ions, you can
date bone going back

00:58:02.350 --> 00:58:04.473
a few hundred thousand years.

00:58:06.010 --> 00:58:10.230
But if we're talking
about the formations that

00:58:10.230 --> 00:58:15.450
are millions of years old-- say
early Pleistocene formations,

00:58:15.450 --> 00:58:19.270
Pliocene formations,
Miocene formations,

00:58:19.270 --> 00:58:21.430
there's no method
that will allow

00:58:21.430 --> 00:58:24.035
you to directly date the bone.

00:58:25.840 --> 00:58:32.240
Now, let's look, for example,
at the Castenedolo discoveries

00:58:32.240 --> 00:58:37.795
from Italy, where Professor
Ragazzoni found human bones

00:58:37.795 --> 00:58:42.070
in layers of rock from
the early Pliocene

00:58:42.070 --> 00:58:44.610
Period, or middle
Pliocene Period.

00:58:45.830 --> 00:58:50.860
There were attempts about
40 years ago to date

00:58:50.860 --> 00:58:55.010
those bones using the
radiocarbon method,

00:58:55.010 --> 00:58:57.000
and a young age was obtained.

00:58:58.140 --> 00:59:02.850
Now, the problem
with that is if you

00:59:02.850 --> 00:59:07.350
have a bone that really is,
say four million years old,

00:59:07.350 --> 00:59:09.670
and it gets contaminated
with the least

00:59:09.670 --> 00:59:12.940
amount of modern
carbon-14-- which

00:59:12.940 --> 00:59:17.510
can happen in numerous ways
through the groundwater,

00:59:17.510 --> 00:59:21.530
through just even a
scientist touching

00:59:21.530 --> 00:59:25.080
the bone it can contaminate
it with recent carbon.

00:59:25.080 --> 00:59:30.570
Then even if the bone really
is, say, four million years old,

00:59:30.570 --> 00:59:32.640
if it's gotten
contaminated with the least

00:59:32.640 --> 00:59:37.230
amount of modern carbon, which
can take place through bacteria

00:59:37.230 --> 00:59:40.790
infiltrating it, through
any number of methods,

00:59:40.790 --> 00:59:45.390
it will show an age of
100,000 years or less.

00:59:45.390 --> 00:59:49.900
So each case has to be
looked at very carefully.

00:59:51.100 --> 00:59:58.440
So there are cases--
but as I said,

00:59:58.440 --> 01:00:03.860
the methods that you can
use to directly date bone

01:00:03.860 --> 01:00:10.355
are limited to bones of, say, a
few thousand years old or less.

01:00:11.490 --> 01:00:14.330
For many the cases
that I'm talking about,

01:00:14.330 --> 01:00:16.190
the appropriate
method is to date

01:00:16.190 --> 01:00:20.270
the age of the formation
at which the bone is found

01:00:20.270 --> 01:00:22.080
and show it's not intrusive.

01:00:23.440 --> 01:00:26.830
AUDIENCE: But you could say,
OK, well this layer is more

01:00:26.830 --> 01:00:29.360
than 300,000 or
400,000 years old,

01:00:29.360 --> 01:00:33.890
and the bone is shown to
be greater than 300,000,

01:00:33.890 --> 01:00:35.510
something greater than 300,000.

01:00:35.510 --> 01:00:37.715
But are there any
cases like that, then?

01:00:39.050 --> 01:00:42.000
MICHAEL CREMO: I can't
think of any right offhand

01:00:42.000 --> 01:00:48.450
because usually the attempt
is to show the bone is,

01:00:48.450 --> 01:00:51.650
in the kinds of cases
that I'm dealing with,

01:00:51.650 --> 01:00:56.290
there are attempts to
show that bone is not

01:00:56.290 --> 01:01:00.710
as old as it's purported to be.

01:01:00.710 --> 01:01:02.940
Undoubtedly, there
are cases like that.

01:01:02.940 --> 01:01:10.030
But I can't-- I'm not able to
give you one right off the top

01:01:10.030 --> 01:01:10.850
of my head.

01:01:12.270 --> 01:01:15.240
AUDIENCE: I'm curious whether,
from your perspective,

01:01:15.240 --> 01:01:18.350
the scientific evidence is
sufficient to convince you

01:01:18.350 --> 01:01:19.800
by itself.

01:01:19.800 --> 01:01:22.290
And if it is sufficient
to convince you by itself,

01:01:22.290 --> 01:01:24.990
then why refer to the
Vedic texts at all?

01:01:24.990 --> 01:01:27.360
Is there something special
about the Vedic texts

01:01:27.360 --> 01:01:32.810
that mystical texts from
other cultures lack?

01:01:33.407 --> 01:01:34.240
MICHAEL CREMO: Yeah.

01:01:34.240 --> 01:01:36.100
It's a very good question.

01:01:36.100 --> 01:01:43.160
And I am open about what my
epistemological commitments

01:01:43.160 --> 01:01:43.660
are.

01:01:45.500 --> 01:01:51.300
And if we study the
Vedic epistemology,

01:01:51.300 --> 01:01:57.370
it tells us there are different
ways of getting evidence.

01:01:57.370 --> 01:01:59.320
There are different
categories of evidence.

01:02:00.120 --> 01:02:01.120
They're called pramanas.

01:02:02.480 --> 01:02:04.490
One is called the
pratyaksha pramana.

01:02:04.490 --> 01:02:07.050
That means sense
evidence, things

01:02:07.050 --> 01:02:09.075
we can touch, see, measure.

01:02:10.540 --> 01:02:15.180
Then there's anumana, which
means logical inference.

01:02:15.180 --> 01:02:18.300
If it's like this and this,
then it must be like that.

01:02:19.660 --> 01:02:23.120
These methods for getting
knowledge about-- especially

01:02:23.120 --> 01:02:26.010
about things that are beyond
the range of the senses,

01:02:26.010 --> 01:02:30.810
like what was happening millions
or billions of years ago,

01:02:30.810 --> 01:02:32.595
they become problematic.

01:02:34.150 --> 01:02:38.890
And therefore, according
to the Vedic epistemology,

01:02:38.890 --> 01:02:42.743
one can rely upon another
type of evidence-- testimony.

01:02:44.530 --> 01:02:47.440
It's called the
sabda pramana, which

01:02:47.440 --> 01:02:52.290
is based on the idea there
is some kind of higher

01:02:52.290 --> 01:02:54.910
intelligence that is
aware of these things

01:02:54.910 --> 01:02:58.510
and can communicate
information about them.

01:02:58.510 --> 01:03:04.160
And that's considered to be
a higher kind of evidence.

01:03:04.160 --> 01:03:12.150
However, as I said, that is not
the epistemological assumption

01:03:12.150 --> 01:03:14.800
that's dominant today
in the world of science.

01:03:14.800 --> 01:03:18.180
If you actually go back
in European science,

01:03:18.180 --> 01:03:22.600
even to 300 or 400
years ago, you'll

01:03:22.600 --> 01:03:26.890
find that many of
the scientists had

01:03:26.890 --> 01:03:33.900
similar epistemological
commitments where they were--

01:03:33.900 --> 01:03:40.640
I mean, even, say, somebody like
Michael Faraday, a physicist

01:03:40.640 --> 01:03:47.457
who did a lot of the work
that unified electricity

01:03:47.457 --> 01:03:48.040
and magnetism.

01:03:49.060 --> 01:03:53.020
He worked along with
Maxwell to come up

01:03:53.020 --> 01:03:57.750
with the electromagnetic
field equations.

01:03:59.610 --> 01:04:03.670
The reason why he
started looking for unity

01:04:03.670 --> 01:04:06.620
was because he was a member
of a Christian sect called

01:04:06.620 --> 01:04:10.620
the Sandemanians, who had the
idea that all energies are

01:04:10.620 --> 01:04:11.820
unified in God.

01:04:13.310 --> 01:04:17.240
So based on his
spiritual conviction

01:04:17.240 --> 01:04:23.120
that energies are
unified, he was

01:04:23.120 --> 01:04:28.000
inspired to do the work
that led to his integration

01:04:28.000 --> 01:04:30.380
of electricity and magnetism.

01:04:30.380 --> 01:04:34.380
And he also tried to bring
gravity into the equation.

01:04:34.380 --> 01:04:36.790
It's something that's still
troubling physicists today,

01:04:36.790 --> 01:04:42.090
how to bring gravity
into the whole picture.

01:04:45.640 --> 01:04:49.790
But I understand that's not
the dominant epistemological

01:04:49.790 --> 01:04:51.330
position today.

01:04:51.330 --> 01:04:53.330
So I put that aside.

01:04:54.480 --> 01:04:57.210
But you're asking me why.

01:04:57.210 --> 01:05:04.430
Say if-- so my
position is I'm going

01:05:04.430 --> 01:05:08.930
to represent an idea
from the Vedic text

01:05:08.930 --> 01:05:13.510
if there is any evidence that
can be used to justify it.

01:05:13.510 --> 01:05:15.280
If there were no
evidence, then I

01:05:15.280 --> 01:05:20.230
wouldn't have anything to say
about it in scientific circles.

01:05:22.202 --> 01:05:25.070
On my own, I might still
have the conviction

01:05:25.070 --> 01:05:27.020
that that's true.

01:05:27.020 --> 01:05:31.340
But I might stop trying
to represent that idea.

01:05:31.340 --> 01:05:35.490
Say if somebody could convince
me that there is absolutely

01:05:35.490 --> 01:05:41.130
no archaeological evidence
for extreme human antiquity,

01:05:41.130 --> 01:05:46.200
